1(RXVT)                             X Tools                            1(RXVT)

NNAAMMEE
       rxvt (ouR XVT) - a VT102 emulator for the X window system

SSYYNNOOPPSSIISS
       rrxxvvtt [options] [-e command [ args ]]

DDEESSCCRRIIPPTTIIOONN
       rrxxvvtt, version 22..66..44, is a colour vt102 terminal emulator intended as an
       _x_t_e_r_m(1) replacement for users who do not require features such as
       Tektronix 4014 emulation and toolkit-style configurability.  As a
       result, rrxxvvtt uses much less swap space -- a significant advantage on a
       machine serving many X sessions.

OOPPTTIIOONNSS
       The rrxxvvtt options (mostly a subset of _x_t_e_r_m's) are listed below.  In
       keeping with the smaller-is-better philosophy, options may be
       eliminated or default values chosen at compile-time, so options and
       defaults listed may not accurately reflect the version installed on
       your system.  `rxvt -h' gives a list of major compile-time options on
       the usage line.  Option descriptions may be prefixed with which compile
       option each is dependent upon.  e.g. `Compile _X_I_M:' requires _X_I_M on the
       usage line.  Note: `rxvt -help' gives a list of all options compiled
       into your version.

       Note that rrxxvvtt permits the resource name to be used as a long-option
       (--/++ option) so the potential command-line options are far greater
       than those listed.  For example: `rxvt --loginShell --color1 Orange'.

       --hheellpp, ----hheellpp
              Print out a message describing available options.

       --ddiissppllaayy _d_i_s_p_l_a_y_n_a_m_e
              Attempt to open a window on the named X display (--dd still
              respected).  In the absence of this option, the display
              specified by the DDIISSPPLLAAYY environment variable is used.

       --ggeeoommeettrryy _g_e_o_m
              Window geometry (--gg still respected); resource ggeeoommeettrryy.

       --rrvv|++rrvv
              Turn on/off simulated reverse video; resource rreevveerrsseeVViiddeeoo.

       --iipp|++iipp
              Turn on/off inheriting parent window's pixmap.  Alternative form
              is --ttrr; resource iinnhheerriittPPiixxmmaapp.

       --bbgg _c_o_l_o_u_r
              Window background colour; resource bbaacckkggrroouunndd.

       --ffgg _c_o_l_o_u_r
              Window foreground colour; resource ffoorreeggrroouunndd.

       --ppiixxmmaapp:: _f_i_l_e_[_;_g_e_o_m_]
              Compile _X_P_M: Specify XPM file for the background and also
              optionally specify its scaling with a geometry string.  Note you
              may need to add quotes to avoid special shell interpretation of
              the `;' in the command-line; resource bbaacckkggrroouunnddPPiixxmmaapp.

       --ccrr _c_o_l_o_u_r
              The cursor colour; resource ccuurrssoorrCCoolloorr.

       --pprr _c_o_l_o_u_r
              The mouse pointer colour; resource ppooiinntteerrCCoolloorr.

       --bbdd _c_o_l_o_u_r
              The colour of the border between the xterm scrollbar and the
              text; resource bboorrddeerrCCoolloorr.

       --ffnn _f_o_n_t_n_a_m_e
              Main normal text font; resource ffoonntt.

       --ffbb _f_o_n_t_n_a_m_e
              Main bold text font; resource bboollddFFoonntt.

       --ffmm _f_o_n_t_n_a_m_e
              Main multicharacter font; resource mmffoonntt.

       --kkmm _m_o_d_e
              Multiple-character font-set encoding mode; eeuuccjj: EUC Japanese
              encoding.  ssjjiiss: Shift JIS encoding; resource
              mmuullttiicchhaarr__eennccooddiinngg.

       --ggrrkk _m_o_d_e
              Greek keyboard translation; iissoo: ISO-8859 mapping.  iibbmm: IBM-437
              mapping; resource ggrreeeekk__kkeeyybbooaarrdd.

       --nnaammee _n_a_m_e
              Specify the application name under which resources are to be
              obtained, rather than the default executable file name.  Name
              should not contain `.' or `*' characters.  Also sets the icon
              and title name.

       --llss|++llss
              Start as a login-shell/sub-shell; resource llooggiinnSShheellll.

       --uutt|++uutt
              Compile _u_t_m_p: Inhibit/enable writing a utmp entry; resource
              uuttmmppIInnhhiibbiitt.

       --vvbb|++vvbb
              Turn on/off visual bell on receipt of a bell character; resource
              vviissuuaallBBeellll.

       --ssbb|++ssbb
              Turn on/off scrollbar; resource ssccrroollllBBaarr.

       --ssii|++ssii
              Turn on/off scroll-to-bottom on TTY output inhibit; resource
              ssccrroollllTTttyyOOuuttppuutt has opposite effect.

       --sskk|++sskk
              Turn on/off scroll-to-bottom on keypress; resource
              ssccrroollllTTttyyKKeeyypprreessss.

       --ssrr|++ssrr
              Put scrollbar on right/left; resource ssccrroollllBBaarr__rriigghhtt.

       --sstt|++sstt
              Display normal (non XTerm/NeXT) scrollbar without/with a trough;
              resource ssccrroollllBBaarr__ffllooaattiinngg.

       --iiccoonniicc
              Start iconified, if the window manager supports that option.
              Alternative form is --iicc.

       --ssll _n_u_m_b_e_r
              Save _n_u_m_b_e_r lines in the scrollback buffer; resource ssaavveeLLiinneess.

       --ttnn _t_e_r_m_n_a_m_e
              This option specifies the name of the terminal type to be set in
              the TTEERRMM environment variable. This terminal type must exist in
              the _t_e_r_m_c_a_p_(_5_) database and should have _l_i_# and _c_o_# entries;
              resource tteerrmmNNaammee.

       --ee _c_o_m_m_a_n_d _[_a_r_g_u_m_e_n_t_s_]
              Run the command with its command-line arguments in the rrxxvvtt
              window; also sets the window title and icon name to be the
              basename of the program being executed if neither _-_t_i_t_l_e (_-_T)
              nor _-_n are given on the command line.  If this option is used,
              it must be the last on the command-line.  If there is no --ee
              option then the default is to run the program specified by the
              SSHHEELLLL environment variable or, failing that, _s_h_(_1_).

       --ttiittllee _t_e_x_t
              Window title (--TT still respected); the default title is the
              basename of the program specified after the --ee option, if any,
              otherwise the application name; resource ttiittllee.

       --nn _t_e_x_t
              Icon name; the default name is the basename of the program
              specified after the --ee option, if any, otherwise the application
              name; resource iiccoonnNNaammee.

       --CC     Capture system console messages.

       --pptt _s_t_y_l_e
              Compile _X_I_M: input style for input method; OOvveerrTThheeSSppoott,
              OOffffTThheeSSppoott, RRoooott; resource pprreeeeddiittTTyyppee.

       --iimm _t_e_x_t
              Compile _X_I_M: input method name.  resource iinnppuuttMMeetthhoodd.

       --mmoodd _m_o_d_i_f_i_e_r
              Override detection of Meta modifier with specified key: aalltt,
              mmeettaa, hhyyppeerr, ssuuppeerr, mmoodd11, mmoodd22, mmoodd33, mmoodd44, mmoodd55; resource
              _m_o_d_i_f_i_e_r.

       --xxrrmm _r_e_s_o_u_r_c_e_s_t_r_i_n_g
              No effect on rxvt.  Simply passes through an argument to be made
              available in the instance's argument list.  Appears in
              _W_M___C_O_M_M_A_N_D in some window managers.

RREESSOOUURRCCEESS ((aavvaaiillaabbllee aallssoo aass lloonngg--ooppttiioonnss))
       Note: `rxvt --help' gives a list of all resources (long options)
       compiled into your version.  If compiled with internal Xresources
       support (i.e. rrxxvvtt --hh lists ..XXddeeffaauullttss) then rrxxvvtt accepts application
       defaults set in XAPPLOADDIR/Rxvt (compile-time defined: usually
       //uussrr//lliibb//XX1111//aapppp--ddeeffaauullttss//RRxxvvtt) and resources set in ~~//..XXddeeffaauullttss, or
       ~~//..XXrreessoouurrcceess if ~~//..XXddeeffaauullttss does not exist.  Note that when reading X
       resources, rrxxvvtt recognizes two class names: XXTTeerrmm and RRxxvvtt.  The class
       name XXTTeerrmm allows resources common to both rrxxvvtt and _x_t_e_r_m to be easily
       configured, while the class name RRxxvvtt allows resources unique to rrxxvvtt,
       notably colours and key-handling, to be shared between different rrxxvvtt
       configurations.  If no resources are specified, suitable defaults will
       be used.  Command-line arguments can be used to override resource
       settings.  The following resources are allowed:

       ggeeoommeettrryy:: _g_e_o_m
              Create the window with the specified X window geometry [default
              80x24]; option --ggeeoommeettrryy.

       bbaacckkggrroouunndd:: _c_o_l_o_u_r
              Use the specified colour as the window's background colour
              [default White]; option --bbgg.

       ffoorreeggrroouunndd:: _c_o_l_o_u_r
              Use the specified colour as the window's foreground colour
              [default Black]; option --ffgg.

       ccoolloorr_n:: _c_o_l_o_u_r
              Use the specified colour for the colour value _n, where 0-7
              corresponds to low-intensity (normal) colours and 8-15
              corresponds to high-intensity (bold = bright foreground, blink =
              bright background) colours.  The canonical names are as follows:
              0=black, 1=red, 2=green, 3=yellow, 4=blue, 5=magenta, 6=cyan,
              7=white, but the actual colour names used are listed in the
              CCOOLLOORRSS AANNDD GGRRAAPPHHIICCSS section.

       ccoolloorrBBDD:: _c_o_l_o_u_r
              Use the specified colour to display bold characters when the
              foreground colour is the default.

       ccoolloorrUULL:: _c_o_l_o_u_r
              Use the specified colour to display underlined characters when
              the foreground colour is the default.

       ccuurrssoorrCCoolloorr:: _c_o_l_o_u_r
              Use the specified colour for the cursor.  The default is to use
              the foreground colour; option --ccrr.

       ccuurrssoorrCCoolloorr22:: _c_o_l_o_u_r
              Use the specified colour for the colour of the cursor text.  For
              this to take effect, ccuurrssoorrCCoolloorr must also be specified.  The
              default is to use the background colour.

       rreevveerrsseeVViiddeeoo:: _b_o_o_l_e_a_n
              TTrruuee: simulate reverse video by foreground and background
              colours; option --rrvv, FFaallssee: regular screen colours [default];
              option ++rrvv.  See note in CCOOLLOORRSS AANNDD GGRRAAPPHHIICCSS section.

       iinnhheerriittPPiixxmmaapp:: _b_o_o_l_e_a_n
              TTrruuee: make the background inherit the parent windows' pixmap,
              giving artificial transparency.  FFaallssee: do not inherit the
              parent windows' pixmap.

       ssccrroollllCCoolloorr:: _c_o_l_o_u_r
              Use the specified colour for the scrollbar [default #B2B2B2].

       ttrroouugghhCCoolloorr:: _c_o_l_o_u_r
              Use the specified colour for the scrollbar's trough area
              [default #969696].  Only relevant for normal (non XTerm/NeXT)
              scrollbar.

       bbaacckkggrroouunnddPPiixxmmaapp:: _f_i_l_e_[_;_g_e_o_m_]
              Use the specified XPM file (note the `.xpm' extension is
              optional) for the background and also optionally specify its
              scaling with a geometry string WWxxHH++XX++YY, in which ""WW"" // ""HH""
              specify the horizontal/vertical scale (percent) and ""XX"" // ""YY""
              locate the image centre (percent).  A scale of 0 displays the
              image with tiling.  A scale of 1 displays the image without any
              scaling.  A scale of 2 to 9 specifies an integer number of
              images in that direction.  No image will be magnified beyond 10
              times its original size.  The maximum permitted scale is 1000.
              [default 0x0+50+50]

       mmeennuu:: _f_i_l_e_[_;_t_a_g_]
              Read in the specified menu file (note the `.menu' extension is
              optional) and also optionally specify a starting tag to find.
              See the reference documentation for details on the syntax for
              the menuBar.

       ppaatthh:: _p_a_t_h
              Specify the colon-delimited search path for finding files (XPM
              and menus), in addition to the paths specified by the RRXXVVTTPPAATTHH
              and PPAATTHH environment variables.

       ffoonntt:: _f_o_n_t_n_a_m_e
              Select the main text font used [default 7x14]; option --ffnn.

       ffoonntt_n:: _f_o_n_t_n_a_m_e
              Specify the alternative font _n.  The default font values:

 \!.3rmk "\$1"
\!.nr 3crow 0
\!.3rvpt "\$1"
ffoonntt:                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                7x14

\!.3rvpt "\$1"

\!.nr 3brule 1


\!.3rvpt "\$1"

\!.3rmk "\$1"
\!.nr 3crow 1
\!.3rvpt "\$1"
ffoonntt11:                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                6x10

\!.3rvpt "\$1"

\!.nr 3brule 1


\!.3rvpt "\$1"

\!.3rmk "\$1"
\!.nr 3crow 2
\!.3rvpt "\$1"
ffoonntt22:                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                6x13

\!.3rvpt "\$1"

\!.nr 3brule 1


\!.3rvpt "\$1"

\!.3rmk "\$1"
\!.nr 3crow 3
\!.3rvpt "\$1"
ffoonntt33:                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                8x13

\!.3rvpt "\$1"

\!.nr 3brule 1


\!.3rvpt "\$1"

\!.3rmk "\$1"
\!.nr 3crow 4
\!.3rvpt "\$1"
ffoonntt44:                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                9x15

\!.3rvpt "\$1"

\!.nr 3brule 1


\!.3rvpt "\$1"



\!.3rvpt "\$1"

       bboollddFFoonntt:: _f_o_n_t_n_a_m_e
              Specify the name of the bold font to use if ccoolloorrBBDD has not been
              specified and it is not possible to map the default foreground colour
              to colour 8-15 [default NONE].  This font must be the same height and
              width as the normal font;
              option --ffbb.

       mmffoonntt:: _f_o_n_t_n_a_m_e
              Select the main multiple-character text font used [default k14];
              option --ffkk.

       mmffoonntt_n:: _f_o_n_t_n_a_m_e
              Specify the alternative multiple-character font _n.  If compiled
              for multiple-character fonts, the Roman and multiple-character font
              sizes should match.

       mmuullttiicchhaarr__eennccooddiinngg:: _m_o_d_e
              Set the encoding mode to be used when multicharacter encoding is
              received;
              eeuuccjj: EUC Japanese encoding [default for Kanji].
              ssjjiiss: Shift JIS encoding.
              bbiigg55: BIG5 encoding.
              ggbb: GB encoding;
              option --kkmm.

       ggrreeeekk__kkeeyybbooaarrdd:: _m_o_d_e
              Set the Greek keyboard translation mode to be used;
              iissoo: ISO-8859 mapping (elot-928) [default].
              iibbmm: IBM-437 mapping (DOS codepage 737);
              option --ggrrkk.
              Use MMooddee__sswwiittcchh to toggle keyboard input.  For more details,
              see the distributed file RREEAADDMMEE..ggrreeeekk.

       sseelleeccttssttyyllee:: _t_e_x_t
              Set mouse selection style to oolldd which is 2.20, oollddwwoorrdd which
              is xterm style with 2.20 old word selection, or anything else which
              gives xterm style selection.

       ttiittllee:: _t_e_x_t
              Set window title string, the default title is the command-line
              specified after the --ee option, if any, otherwise the application
              name;
              option --ttiittllee.

       iiccoonnNNaammee:: _t_e_x_t
              Set the name used to label the window's icon or displayed in an icon
              manager window, it also sets the window's title unless it is
              explicitly set;
              option --nn.

       mmaappAAlleerrtt:: _b_o_o_l_e_a_n
              TTrruuee: de-iconify (map) on receipt of a bell character.
              FFaallssee: no de-iconify (map) on receipt of a bell character
              [default].

       vviissuuaallBBeellll:: _b_o_o_l_e_a_n
              TTrruuee: use visual bell on receipt of a bell character;
              option --vvbb.
              FFaallssee: no visual bell [default];
              option ++vvbb.

       llooggiinnSShheellll:: _b_o_o_l_e_a_n
              TTrruuee: start as a login shell by prepending a `-' to aarrggvv[[00]]
              of the shell;
              option --llss.
              FFaallssee: start as a normal sub-shell [default];
              option ++llss.

       uuttmmppIInnhhiibbiitt:: _b_o_o_l_e_a_n
              TTrruuee: inhibit writing record into the system log file uuttmmpp;
              option --uutt.
              FFaallssee: write record into the system log file uuttmmpp [default];
              option ++uutt.

       pprriinntt--ppiippee:: _s_t_r_i_n_g
              Specify a command pipe for vt100 printer [default _l_p_r_(_1_)].  Use
              PPrriinntt to initiate a screen dump to the printer and CCttrrll--PPrriinntt
              or SShhiifftt--PPrriinntt to include the scrollback as well.

       ssccrroollllBBaarr:: _b_o_o_l_e_a_n
              TTrruuee: enable the scrollbar [default];
              option --ssbb.
              FFaallssee: disable the scrollbar;
              option ++ssbb.

       ssccrroollllBBaarr__rriigghhtt:: _b_o_o_l_e_a_n
              TTrruuee: place the scrollbar on the right of the window;
              option --ssrr.
              FFaallssee: place the scrollbar on the left of the window;
              option ++ssrr.

       ssccrroollllBBaarr__ffllooaattiinngg:: _b_o_o_l_e_a_n
              TTrruuee: display an rxvt scrollbar without a trough;
              option --sstt.
              FFaallssee: display an rxvt scrollbar with a trough;
              option ++sstt.

       ssccrroollllTTttyyOOuuttppuutt:: _b_o_o_l_e_a_n
              TTrruuee: scroll to bottom when tty receives output;
              option(+si).
              FFaallssee: do not scroll to bottom when tty receives output;
              option(-si).

       ssccrroollllTTttyyKKeeyypprreessss:: _b_o_o_l_e_a_n
              TTrruuee: scroll to bottom when a non-special key is pressed.
              Special keys are those which are intercepted by rxvt for special
              handling and are not passed onto the shell;
              option(-sk).
              FFaallssee: do not scroll to bottom when a non-special key is pressed;
              option(+sk).

       ssmmaallllffoonntt__kkeeyy:: _k_e_y_s_y_m
              If enabled, use AAlltt--_k_e_y_s_y_m to toggle to a smaller font
              [default AAlltt--<<]

       bbiiggffoonntt__kkeeyy:: _k_e_y_s_y_m
              If enabled, use AAlltt--_k_e_y_s_y_m to toggle to a bigger font
              [default AAlltt-->>]

       ssaavveeLLiinneess:: _n_u_m_b_e_r
              Save _n_u_m_b_e_r lines in the scrollback buffer [default 64];
              option --ssll.

       tteerrmmNNaammee:: _t_e_r_m_n_a_m_e
              Specifies the terminal type name to be set in the TTEERRMM
              environment variable;
              option --ttnn.

       mmeettaa88:: _b_o_o_l_e_a_n
              TTrruuee: handle Meta (Alt) + keypress to set the 8th bit.
              FFaallssee: handle Meta (Alt) + keypress as an escape prefix [default].

       bbaacckkssppaacceekkeeyy:: _s_t_r_i_n_g
              The string to send when the backspace key is pressed.  If set to
              DDEECC or unset it will send DDeelleettee (code 127) or, if shifted,
              BBaacckkssppaaccee (code 8) - which can be reversed with the appropriate
              DEC private mode escape sequence.

       ddeelleetteekkeeyy:: _s_t_r_i_n_g
              The string to send when the delete key (not the keypad delete key) is
              pressed.  If unset it will send the sequence traditionally associated
              with the EExxeeccuuttee key.

       ccuuttcchhaarrss:: _s_t_r_i_n_g
              The characters used as delimiters for double-click word selection.
              The built-in default:
              BBAACCKKSSLLAASSHH ``""''&&(())**,,;;<<==>>??@@[[]]{{||}}

       pprreeeeddiittTTyyppee:: _s_t_y_l_e
              OOvveerrTThheeSSppoott, OOffffTThheeSSppoott, RRoooott;
              option --pptt.

       iinnppuuttMMeetthhoodd:: _n_a_m_e
              _n_a_m_e of inputMethod to use;
              option --iimm.

       mmooddiiffiieerr:: _m_o_d_i_f_i_e_r
              Set the key to be interpreted as the Meta key to:
              aalltt, mmeettaa, hhyyppeerr, ssuuppeerr, mmoodd11, mmoodd22, mmoodd33,
              mmoodd44, mmoodd55;
              option --mmoodd.

       kkeeyyssyymm.._s_y_m: _s_t_r_i_n_g
              Associate _s_t_r_i_n_g with keysym _s_y_m (00xxFFFF0000 -- 00xxFFFFFFFF).  It
              may contain escape values (\a: bell, \b: backspace, \e, \E: escape,
              \n: newline, \r: return, \t: tab, \000: octal number) or control
              characters (^?: delete, ^@: null, ^A ...) and may enclosed with
              double quotes so that it can start or end with whitespace.  The
              intervening resource name kkeeyyssyymm.. cannot be omitted.  This
              resource is only available when compiled with KEYSYM_RESOURCE.

TTHHEE SSCCRROOLLLLBBAARR
       Lines of text that scroll off the top of the rrxxvvtt window (resource:
       ssaavveeLLiinneess) and can be scrolled back using the scrollbar or by
       keystrokes.  The normal rrxxvvtt scrollbar has arrows and its behaviour is
       fairly intuitive.  The xxtteerrmm--ssccrroollllbbaarr is without arrows and its
       behaviour mimics that of _x_t_e_r_m

       Scroll down with BBuuttttoonn11 (xxtteerrmm--ssccrroollllbbaarr) or SShhiifftt--NNeexxtt.  Scroll up
       with BBuuttttoonn33 (xxtteerrmm--ssccrroollllbbaarr) or SShhiifftt--PPrriioorr.  Continuous scroll with
       BBuuttttoonn22.

MMOOUUSSEE RREEPPOORRTTIINNGG
       To temporarily override mouse reporting, for either the scrollbar or
       the normal text selection/insertion, hold either the Shift or the Meta
       (Alt) key while performing the desired mouse action.

       If mouse reporting mode is active, the normal scrollbar actions are
       disabled -- on the assumption that we are using a fullscreen
       application.  Instead, pressing Button1 and Button3 sends EESSCC[[66~~ (Next)
       and EESSCC[[55~~ (Prior), respectively.  Similarly, clicking on the up and
       down arrows sends EESSCC[[AA (Up) and EESSCC[[BB (Down), respectively.

TTEEXXTT SSEELLEECCTTIIOONN AANNDD IINNSSEERRTTIIOONN
       The behaviour of text selection and insertion mechanism is similar to
       _x_t_e_r_m(1).

       SSeelleeccttiioonn:
              Left click at the beginning of the region, drag to the end of
              the region and release; Right click to extend the marked region;
              Left double-click to select a word; Left triple-click to select
              the entire line.

       IInnsseerrttiioonn:
              Pressing and releasing the Middle mouse button (or SShhiifftt--IInnsseerrtt)
              in an rrxxvvtt window causes the current text selection to be
              inserted as if it had been typed on the keyboard.

CCHHAANNGGIINNGG FFOONNTTSS
       You can change fonts on-the-fly, which is to say cycle through the
       default font and others of various sizes, by using SShhiifftt--KKPP__AAdddd and
       SShhiifftt--KKPP__SSuubbttrraacctt.  Or, alternatively (if enabled) with AAlltt-->> and
       AAlltt--<<, where the actual key can be selected using resources
       ssmmaallllffoonntt__kkeeyy/bbiiggffoonntt__kkeeyy.

LLOOGGIINN SSTTAAMMPP
       rrxxvvtt tries to write an entry into the _u_t_m_p(5) file so that it can be
       seen via the _w_h_o_(_1_) command, and can accept messages.  To allow this
       feature, rrxxvvtt must be installed setuid root on some systems.

CCOOLLOORRSS AANNDD GGRRAAPPHHIICCSS
       If graphics support was enabled at compile-time, rrxxvvtt can be queried
       with ANSI escape sequences and can address individual pixels instead of
       text characters.  Note the graphics support is still considered beta
       code.

       In addition to the default foreground and background colours, rrxxvvtt can
       display up to 16 colours (8 ANSI colours plus high-intensity bold/blink
       versions of the same).  Here is a list of the colours with their
       rrggbb..ttxxtt names.

\!.3rmk "\$1"
\!.nr 3crow 0
\!.3rvpt "\$1"
ccoolloorr00                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                (black) = Black

\!.3rvpt "\$1"

\!.nr 3brule 1


\!.3rvpt "\$1"

\!.3rmk "\$1"
\!.nr 3crow 1
\!.3rvpt "\$1"
ccoolloorr11                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                (red)   = Red3

\!.3rvpt "\$1"

